<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry" title=3D"Geometry"=
>geometry</a>, a <b>trapezoid</b> (<span class=3D"rt-commentedText nowrap">=
<span class=3D"IPA nopopups noexcerpt" lang=3D"en-fonipa"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA/English" title=3D"Help:IPA/English">/<span=
 style=3D"border-bottom:1px dotted"><span title=3D"/=CB=88/: primary stress=
 follows">=CB=88</span><span title=3D"'t' in 'tie'">t</span><span title=3D"=
'r' in 'rye'">r</span><span title=3D"/=C3=A6/: 'a' in 'bad'">=C3=A6</span><=
span title=3D"'p' in 'pie'">p</span><span title=3D"/=C9=99/: 'a' in 'about'=
">=C9=99</span><span title=3D"'z' in 'zoom'">z</span><span title=3D"/=C9=94=
=C9=AA/: 'oi' in 'choice'">=C9=94=C9=AA</span><span title=3D"'d' in 'dye'">=
d</span></span>/</a></span></span>) in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/North_American_English" title=3D"North American English">North America=
n English</a>, or <b>trapezium</b> (<span class=3D"rt-commentedText nowrap"=
><span class=3D"IPA nopopups noexcerpt" lang=3D"en-fonipa"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA/English" title=3D"Help:IPA/English">/<spa=
n style=3D"border-bottom:1px dotted"><span title=3D"'t' in 'tie'">t</span><=
span title=3D"'r' in 'rye'">r</span><span title=3D"/=C9=99/: 'a' in 'about'=
">=C9=99</span><span title=3D"/=CB=88/: primary stress follows">=CB=88</spa=
n><span title=3D"'p' in 'pie'">p</span><span title=3D"/i=CB=90/: 'ee' in 'f=
leece'">i=CB=90</span><span title=3D"'z' in 'zoom'">z</span><span title=3D"=
/i/: 'y' in 'happy'">i</span><span title=3D"/=C9=99/: 'a' in 'about'">=C9=
=99</span><span title=3D"'m' in 'my'">m</span></span>/</a></span></span>) i=
n <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_English" title=3D"Britis=
h English">British English</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-1"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Quadrilateral" title=3D"Quadrilateral">quadrilateral</a> that =
has at least one pair of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallel_=
(geometry)" title=3D"Parallel (geometry)">parallel</a> sides.
</p><p>The parallel sides are called the <i>bases</i> of the trapezoid.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHopkins189133_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHopkins189133-3"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> The other two sides are called the <i>legs</i><sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-FOOTNOTEHopkins189133_3-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHopkins189133-3"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or <i=
>lateral sides</i>. If the trapezoid is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Parallelogram" title=3D"Parallelogram">parallelogram</a>, then the =
choice of bases and legs is arbitrary.
</p><p>A trapezoid is usually considered to be a <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Convex_polygon" title=3D"Convex polygon">convex</a> quadrila=
teral in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_geometry" title=
=3D"Euclidean geometry">Euclidean geometry</a>, but there are also <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crossed_polygon" title=3D"Crossed polygon=
">crossed</a> cases. If shape <i>ABCD</i> is a convex trapezoid, then <i>AB=
DC</i> is a crossed trapezoid. The metric formulas in this article apply in=
 convex trapezoids.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definitions">Definitions</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTrapezoid&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Definitions"><span>ed=
it</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><i>Trapezoid</i> can be defined exclusively or inclusively. Under an exc=
lusive definition a trapezoid is a quadrilateral having <em>exactly one</em=
> pair of parallel sides, with the other pair of opposite sides non-paralle=
l. Parallelograms including rhombi, rectangles, and squares are then not co=
nsidered to be trapezoids.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEUsiskinGriffin2008[ht=
tpsbooksgooglecombooksidff0nDwAAQBAJpgPA29_29]_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-FOOTNOTEUsiskinGr=
iffin2008[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidff0nDwAAQBAJpgPA29_29]-4"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEAlsinaNelsen2020[httpbooksgooglecombooksidCGDSDw=
AAQBAJpgPA90_90]_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-FOOTNOTEAlsinaNelsen2020[httpbooksgooglecombook=
sidCGDSDwAAQBAJpgPA90_90]-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Under an inclusive definition, a tr=
apezoid is any quadrilateral with <em>at least</em> one pair of parallel si=
des.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ringenberg_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-ringenberg-6"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In a=
n inclusive classification scheme, definitions are hierarchical: a square i=
s a type of rectangle and a type of rhombus, a rectangle or rhombus is a ty=
pe of parallelogram, and every parallelogram is a type of trapezoid.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEAlsinaNelsen2020[httpbooksgooglecombooksidCGDSDwAAQBAJ=
pgPA89_89]_7-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Trapezoid#cite_note-FOOTNOTEAlsinaNelsen2020[httpbooksgooglecombooksidCGD=
SDwAAQBAJpgPA89_89]-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A trapezoid can also be defined as any qu=
adrilateral that is not a parallelogram; this definition is also exclusive =
and is used in Euclid's <i>Elements</i>.
</p><p>Professional mathematicians and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Post-secondary_education" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Post-secondar=
y education">post-secondary</a> geometry textbooks nearly always prefer inc=
lusive definitions and classifications, because they simplify statements an=
d proofs of geometric theorems.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEUsiskinGriffin20=
08[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidff0nDwAAQBAJpgPA32_32]_8-0" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-FOOTNOTEUsis=
kinGriffin2008[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidff0nDwAAQBAJpgPA32_32]-8"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> In primary and secondary education, definitions of <i>rectangle</i> and =
<i>parallelogram</i> are also nearly always inclusive, but an exclusive def=
inition of <i>trapezoid</i> is commonly found.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note=
-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This article us=
es the inclusive definition and considers parallelograms to be special kind=
s of trapezoids. (<abbr title=3D"compare">cf.</abbr> <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadrilateral#Taxonomy" title=3D"Quadrilateral">Quadrila=
teral =C2=A7 Taxonomy</a>)
</p><p>To avoid confusion, some sources use the term <i>proper trapezoid</i=
> to describe trapezoids with exactly one pair of parallel sides, analogous=
 to uses of the word <i>proper</i> in some other mathematical objects.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-12"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Etymology">Etymology</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTrapezoid&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Etymology"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In the ancient Greek geometry of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Euclid%27s_Elements" title=3D"Euclid's Elements">Euclid's <i>Elements</i>=
</a> (<abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr><span style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=
=E2=80=89300</span> BC), quadrilaterals were classified into exclusive cate=
gories: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square" title=3D"Square">s=
quare</a>; oblong (non-square <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rect=
angle" title=3D"Rectangle">rectangle</a>); (non-square) <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhombus" title=3D"Rhombus">rhombus</a>; rhomboid, mea=
ning a non-rhombus non-rectangle <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P=
arallelogram" title=3D"Parallelogram">parallelogram</a>; or trapezium (=CF=
=84=CF=81=CE=B1=CF=80=CE=AD=CE=B6=CE=B9=CE=BF=CE=BD, literally "table"), me=
aning any quadrilateral not already included in the previous categories.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-Murray_13-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-Murray-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The Neoplatonist philosopher <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Proclus" title=3D"Proclus">Proclus</a> (mid 5th century AD) wrote an infl=
uential commentary on Euclid with a richer set of categories, which he attr=
ibuted to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posidonius" title=3D"Pos=
idonius">Posidonius</a> (<abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr><span style=3D"whit=
e-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=89100</span> BC). In this scheme, a quadrilateral c=
an be a parallelogram or a non-parallelogram. A parallelogram can itself be=
 a square, an oblong (non-square rectangle), a rhombus, or a rhomboid (non-=
rhombus non-rectangle). A non-parallelogram can be a <i>trapezium</i> with =
exactly one pair of parallel sides, which can be <i>isosceles</i> (with equ=
al legs) or <i>scalene</i> (with unequal legs); or a <i>trapezoid</i> (=CF=
=84=CF=81=CE=B1=CF=80=CE=B5=CE=B6=CE=BF=CE=B5=CE=B9=CE=B4=CE=AE, literally =
"table-like") with no parallel sides.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Murray_13-1" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note=
-Murray-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Trapezium_and_Trapezoid,_Hutton%E2%80%99s_mis=
take_in_1795.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.=
wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c1/Trapezium_and_Trapezoid%2C_Hutto=
n%E2%80%99s_mistake_in_1795.png/250px-Trapezium_and_Trapezoid%2C_Hutton%E2%=
80%99s_mistake_in_1795.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"89" =
class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1220" data-file-height=3D"436"=
></a><figcaption>Hutton's definitions in 1795</figcaption></figure>
<p>All European languages except American English follow Proclus's meanings=
 of <i>trapezium</i> and <i>trapezoid</i>,.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConw=
ayBurgielGoodman-Strauss2016[httpbooksgooglecombooksidDrj1CwAAQBAJpgPA286_2=
86]_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trap=
ezoid#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConwayBurgielGoodman-Strauss2016[httpbooksgooglecom=
booksidDrj1CwAAQBAJpgPA286_286]-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, the meaning in Bri=
tish English was reversed for much of the 19th century. In 1795, an influen=
tial mathematical dictionary published by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Charles_Hutton" title=3D"Charles Hutton">Charles Hutton</a> transpo=
sed the two terms without explanation, leading to widespread inconsistency.=
 Hutton's change was reverted in British English in about 1875, but it has =
been retained in American English to the present.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Murray=
_13-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezo=
id#cite_note-Murray-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Late 19th century American geometry te=
xtbooks define a trapezium as having <i>no</i> parallel sides, a trapezoid =
as having <i>exactly one</i> pair of parallel sides, and a parallelogram as=
 having two sets of opposing parallel sides.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHop=
kins189133_3-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Trapezoid#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHopkins189133-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-FOOTNOTEHobbs189966_16-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHobbs189966-16"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
To avoid confusion between contradictory British and American meanings of <=
i>trapezium</i> and <i>trapezoid</i>, quadrilaterals with no parallel sides=
 have sometimes been called <i>irregular quadrilaterals</i>.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trape=
zoid#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Special_cases">Special case=
s</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTrapezoid&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Special cases"><s=
pan>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></=
div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Trapezoid_special_cases.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"=
https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Trapezoid_special=
_cases.png/330px-Trapezoid_special_cases.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"2=
80" height=3D"242" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"849" data-f=
ile-height=3D"734"></a><figcaption>Trapezoid special cases. The orange figu=
res also qualify as parallelograms.</figcaption></figure>
<p>An <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isosceles_trapezoid" title=
=3D"Isosceles trapezoid">isosceles trapezoid</a> is a trapezoid where the b=
ase angles have the same measure.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDodge201282_18=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#=
cite_note-FOOTNOTEDodge201282-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-posamentie=
r-bannister_19-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Trapezoid#cite_note-posamentier-bannister-19"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> As a conseque=
nce the two legs are also of equal length and it has <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Reflection_symmetry" title=3D"Reflection symmetry">refle=
ction symmetry</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHopkins189134_20-0" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-FO=
OTNOTEHopkins189134-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This is possible for acute trapezoids =
or right trapezoids as rectangles. An acute trapezoid is a trapezoid with t=
wo adjacent acute angles on its longer base, and the isosceles trapezoid is=
 an example of an acute trapezoid. The isosceles trapezoid has a special ca=
se known as a three-sided trapezoid, meaning it is a trapezoid wherein two =
trapezoid's legs have equal lengths as the trapezoid's base at the top.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEAlsinaNelsen2020[httpbooksgooglecombooksidCGDSDwAAQ=
BAJpgPA90_90&amp;ndash;91]_21-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-FOOTNOTEAlsinaNelsen2020[httpbooksgo=
oglecombooksidCGDSDwAAQBAJpgPA90_90&amp;ndash;91]-21"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The isosc=
eles trapezoid is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convex_hull"=
 title=3D"Convex hull">convex hull</a> of an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Antiparallelogram" title=3D"Antiparallelogram">antiparallelogram=
</a>, a type of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crossed_quadrilate=
ral" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Crossed quadrilateral">crossed quadrila=
teral</a>. Every antiparallelogram is formed with such a trapezoid by repla=
cing two parallel sides by the two diagonals.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEAl=
sinaNelsen2020[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidCGDSDwAAQBAJpgPA212_212]_22-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_no=
te-FOOTNOTEAlsinaNelsen2020[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidCGDSDwAAQBAJpgPA212_2=
12]-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>An obtuse trapezoid, on the other hand, has one acute and one obtuse=
 angle on each base. An example is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Parallelogram" title=3D"Parallelogram">parallelogram</a> with equal acute =
angles.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEAlsinaNelsen2020[httpbooksgooglecombooks=
idCGDSDwAAQBAJpgPA90_90&amp;ndash;91]_21-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-FOOTNOTEAlsinaNelsen2020[=
httpbooksgooglecombooksidCGDSDwAAQBAJpgPA90_90&amp;ndash;91]-21"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p>A right trapezoid is a trapezoid with two adjacent <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Right_angle" title=3D"Right angle">right angle</a>.=
 One special type of right trapezoid is by forming three <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Right_triangle" title=3D"Right triangle">right trian=
gles</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEAlsinaNelsen2020[httpbooksgooglecomboo=
ksidCGDSDwAAQBAJpgPA91_91]_23-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-FOOTNOTEAlsinaNelsen2020[httpbooksgo=
oglecombooksidCGDSDwAAQBAJpgPA91_91]-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> which was used by <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_A._Garfield" title=3D"James A. G=
arfield">James Garfield</a> to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gar=
field%27s_proof_of_the_Pythagorean_theorem" title=3D"Garfield's proof of th=
e Pythagorean theorem">prove</a> the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Pythagorean_theorem" title=3D"Pythagorean theorem">Pythagorean theorem</=
a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2=
4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A <b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tangential_trapezoid" =
title=3D"Tangential trapezoid">tangential trapezoid</a></b> is a trapezoid =
that has an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tangential_quadrilater=
al" title=3D"Tangential quadrilateral">incircle</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Condition_of_existence">Con=
dition of existence</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
