-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:4.557ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle S,\=
,T}"></span> formed by the diagonals</figcaption></figure>
<p>Given a convex quadrilateral, the following properties are equivalent, a=
nd each implies that the quadrilateral is a trapezoid:
</p>
<ul><li>It has two adjacent <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angle"=
 title=3D"Angle">angles</a> that are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Supplementary_angles" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Supplementary angle=
s">supplementary</a>, that is, they add up to 180 <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Degree_(angle)" title=3D"Degree (angle)">degrees</a>.</li>
<li>The angle between a side and a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Diagonal" title=3D"Diagonal">diagonal</a> is equal to the angle between th=
e opposite side and the same diagonal.</li>
<li>The diagonals cut each other in mutually the same <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ratio" title=3D"Ratio">ratio</a> (this ratio is the sam=
e as that between the lengths of the parallel sides).</li>
<li>The diagonals cut the quadrilateral into four <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Triangle" title=3D"Triangle">triangles</a> of which one opp=
osite pair have equal areas.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEJosefsson2013Prop._=
5_27-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapez=
oid#cite_note-FOOTNOTEJosefsson2013Prop._5-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>The product of the areas of the two triangles formed by one diagonal eq=
uals the product of the areas of the two triangles formed by the other diag=
onal.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEJosefsson2013Thm._6_28-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-FOOTNOTEJo=
sefsson2013Thm._6-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>The areas <i>S</i> and <i>T</i> of some two opposite triangles of the f=
our triangles formed by the diagonals satisfy the equation</li></ul>
<dl><dd><dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><s=
pan class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display:=
 none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\dis=
playstyle {\sqrt {K}}=3D{\sqrt {S}}+{\sqrt {T}},}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
