=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>The cotangents of two adjacent angles sum to 0, as do the cotangents of=
 the other two adjacent angles.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEJosefsson201326_=
32-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoi=
d#cite_note-FOOTNOTEJosefsson201326-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>One bimedian divides the quadrilateral into two quadrilaterals of equal=
 areas.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEJosefsson201326_32-1" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-FOOTNOTEJose=
fsson201326-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Twice the length of the bimedian connecting the midpoints of two opposi=
te sides equals the sum of the lengths of the other sides.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-FOOTNOTEJosefsson201331_33-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-FOOTNOTEJosefsson201331-33"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up></li></ul>
<p>Additionally, the following properties are equivalent, and each implies =
that opposite sides <i>a</i> and <i>b</i> are parallel:
</p>
<ul><li>The consecutive sides <i>a</i>, <i>c</i>, <i>b</i>, <i>d</i> and th=
e diagonals <i>p</i>, <i>q</i> satisfy the equation<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOT=
NOTEJosefsson2013Cor._11_34-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-FOOTNOTEJosefsson2013Cor._11-34"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup></li></ul>
