<p>The midsegment of a trapezoid is one of the two <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Quadrilateral#Special_line_segments" title=3D"Quadrilatera=
l">bimedians</a> (the other bimedian divides the trapezoid into equal areas=
).
</p><p>The <i>height</i> (or altitude) is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Perpendicular" title=3D"Perpendicular">perpendicular</a> distan=
ce between the bases.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHopkins189133_3-3" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note=
-FOOTNOTEHopkins189133-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In the case that the two bases have di=
fferent lengths (<i>a</i> =E2=89=A0 <i>b</i>), the height of a trapezoid <i=
>h</i> can be determined by the length of its four sides using the formula<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-Mathworld_38-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-Mathworld-38"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
