wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>When any rectangle is viewed in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Perspective_(graphical)" title=3D"Perspective (graphical)">perspective=
</a> from a position which is centered on one axis but not the other, it ap=
pears to be an isosceles trapezoid, called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Keystone_effect" title=3D"Keystone effect">keystone effect</a>=
 because arch <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keystone_(architectu=
re)" title=3D"Keystone (architecture)">keystones</a> are commonly trapezoid=
al. For example, when a rectangular building <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Fa%C3%A7ade" title=3D"Fa=C3=A7ade">fa=C3=A7ade</a> is photograph=
ed from the ground at a position directly in front using a <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rectilinear_lens" title=3D"Rectilinear lens">recti=
linear lens</a>, the image of the building is an isosceles trapezoid. Such =
photographs sometimes have a "keystone transformation" applied to them to r=
ecover rectangular shapes. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Video_p=
rojector" title=3D"Video projector">Video projectors</a> sometimes apply su=
ch a keystone transformation to the recorded image before projection, so th=
at the image projected on a flat screen appears undistorted.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:14_campidoglio-altointro_(1).=
jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org=
