_campidoglio-altointro_%281%29.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"130" height=
=3D"177" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"400" data-file-height=
=3D"545"></a><figcaption>Piazza del Campidoglio viewed from directly above.=
</figcaption></figure>
<p>Trapezoidal doors and windows were the standard style for the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inca_architecture" title=3D"Inca architectur=
e">Inca</a>, although it can be found used by earlier cultures of the same =
region and did not necessarily originate with them.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-48" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite=
_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-49" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-49"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
An almena, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battlement" title=3D"=
Battlement">battlement</a> feature characteristic of <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Moorish_architecture" title=3D"Moorish architecture">Moo=
rish architecture</a>, is trapezoidal.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECurl19991=
9almena_50-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Trapezoid#cite_note-FOOTNOTECurl199919almena-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
Michaelangelo's redesign of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pi=
azza_del_Campidoglio" title=3D"Piazza del Campidoglio">Piazza del Campidogl=
io</a> (see photograph at right) incorporated a trapezoid surrounding an el=
lipse, giving the effect of a square surrounding a circle when seen foresho=
rtened at ground level.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECurl1999486Michaelangelo=
_Buonarroti_51-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Trapezoid#cite_note-FOOTNOTECurl1999486Michaelangelo_Buonarroti-51"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup>
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cinematography" title=3D"Cinematog=
raphy">Cinematography</a> takes advantage of trapezoids in the opposite way=
, to produce an excessive foreshortening effect from the camera viewpoint, =
giving the illusion of greater depth to a room in a movie studio than the s=
et physically has.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTERam=C3=ADrez201284_52-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_not=
e-FOOTNOTERam%C3%ADrez201284-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
Trapezoids were also used to produce the visual distortions of <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caligarism" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cal=
igarism">Caligarism</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTERam=C3=ADrez201284_52-1=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#ci=
te_note-FOOTNOTERam%C3%ADrez201284-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>52<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canal" title=3D"Canal">Canals</a> =
and drainage <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ditch" title=3D"Ditch=
">ditches</a> commonly have a trapezoidal cross-section.
</p><p>In biology, especially <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morp=
hology_(biology)" title=3D"Morphology (biology)">morphology</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taxonomy_(biology)" title=3D"Taxonomy (bi=
ology)">taxonomy</a>, terms such as <i>trapezoidal</i> or <i>trapeziform</i=
> commonly are useful in descriptions of particular organs or forms.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Capinera2008_53-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoid#cite_note-Capinera2008-53"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Trapezoids are sometimes used as a graphical symbol. In <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circuit_diagram" title=3D"Circuit diagram">cir=
cuit diagrams</a>, a trapezoid is the symbol for a <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Multiplexer" title=3D"Multiplexer">multiplexer</a>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-54" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Trapezoid#cite_note-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> An isosceles trapezoid is used for t=
he shape of road signs, for example, on secondary highways in <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ontario" title=3D"Ontario">Ontario</a>, Canada.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEAlsinaNelsen2020[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidCGDS=
DwAAQBAJpgPA93_93]_55-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
